<br>
For example:<br>
<br>
Dwarves in almost all representations take great pride in their beards, almost to the point of mania.  So, I ask myself things about why, and then work out how this would be reflected in the day to day life of a dwarf.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Questions I would ask might include:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Why is their beard so important to them?<br>
<br>
Do they treat it with anything to protect it from fire?<br>
<br>
Is a beard common to both males and females, or just the males?<br>
<br>
Does color, fullness, length, grooming, or a combination of these traits determine what makes one beard 'better' than another?<br>
<br>
Do the beards in some way reflect heritage, accomplishments in life, sexual prowess, religion or some other aspect of the dwarves day to day existance?<br>
<br>
If they weave ribbons, dye color, or braid some sort of markings to show rank/accomplisments/ancestory into their beards, how long does it take, and is it a daily ritual, or something they only do when new things are added?<br>
<br>
Does grooming change based on what the dwarf is doing at a given moment?<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Things this might mean in their day to day life might include:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Before going onto battle, a dwarf might rebraid his beard into two 'battle braids', wrap them in a leather sleeve to protect them from fire, and tie them together behind his neck, so it doesn't get in the way or get damaged during a fight.  Alternatively, he might groom it especially nicely, in case he is defeated, so it will look good when they carry him off the field of battle.<br>
<br>
Ribbons might be crafted by the women (Maybe something simple like the old 'friendship bracelts' or perhaps something fancy, like very fine and durable lace) for their clan leaders to award for various accomplisments.  These might be set patterns showing standard things, like 'defeated 10 orcs in hand to hand combat' or they might be unique, wherein the colors of the threads show elements and locations, denoting particular battles, mining finds, smithing skill, or some other event.<br>
<br>
A ribbon or threads might be woven in to denote marital status, or certain patterns of braid might denote a heritage.  A narrow double braid down each side of the beard might show one family line, while a thick twisted tail dyed black going down the middle might show a different family tree.  Combinations of these might denote marriages, children, or the loss of a loved one.<br>
<br>
A dwarf who is outcast, might be forcibly shaved and his cheeks scarred deliberately to prevent beard regrowth before his banishment, so that any other dwarf would know he's been dishonored.  This would be a worse fate than death, and might drive many outcasts to suicide.<br>
<br>
A dwarf might wake up evry morning, bathe, comb out his beard, and rebraid it entirely.  This could be a ritual, where the braids were identical every time, or it might be ceremonial, where the daily grooming changes subtly, or dramatically depending on what the plans for the day include, for example is the weave the same for a wedding as it is for combat?<br>
<br>
<br>
Basically, you can do this with the various commonalities you find about dwarves, and define them in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  your</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> way for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  your</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> story.  The larger concepts tend to remain similar in a lot of stories, but the details make the story your own.<br>
<br>
Once you flesh out the details, coming up with things to fill in realistic snapshots of their lives should be almost too easy.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  General questions I would ask would be things like:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
How are they organized?  Clans?  Kingdoms?  Militant?<br>
<br>
How does their religion work?  Is it structured, or passed down by word of mouth?  Shamanic, or institutional?  Are there religious differences, or do different gods have their followers wage war on each other?  Are there 'dark' gods?<br>
<br>
Then look at details in day to day life, like does height, strength, or girth matter to them as much as it does to humans, or is the beard the only way to measure a dwarf that matters?<br>
<br>
How do they feel about the outdoors?  Cities?  Caves?  Boats?  Swimming?  Being airborne?<br>
<br>
How often to they reproduce?  How often do they die?  Is their population increasing, or decreasing?  How quickly?  How concerned are they about it?  How long do they live, naturally?<br>
<br>
What is fashionable attire for dwarves?<br>
<br>
What are the defined gender roles?<br>
<br>
Is drinking a cultural icon?  Do they drink to excess regularly like they are often depicted, or is their high alcohol tolernace due to a lifetime of social drinking, like the europeans or slavic cultures?  Perhaps they drink alcohol because water goes brackish when stored for long periods underground...<br>
<br>
How do they regard the other races?<br>
<br>
<br>
Again, the bottom line is that a lot of the general stuff is fairly common across most literature, since a lot of fiction is based on Tolkien, or Norse mythology, and the two are fairly close in many regards.  The details vary wildly, and if you are looking for a concensus in various stories then you will be disappointed.  Choose what <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  you</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> like, toss out what you don't, and define what remains in your own way.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Make the story your own.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
